This file is the append-only ADR (Architecture Decision Record) ledger for the CTX project — the rationale/rejected-alternatives layer that `intent.md` and other docs point to rather than restate. It records *why*, not *what*; outcomes live in code, generated rollups, and `docs/STATUS.md`.

Structure: numbered `ADR-NNN` entries, strictly append-only — superseded decisions get a new ADR plus a **Status/Supersedes** note on the old one, never a rewrite. Cross-references use `[[ADR-NNN]]` wiki-link style. Entries follow a loose Decision/Rejected/Rationale/Context template but aren't rigidly schematized.

Key facts an editor needs before touching related code or docs:

- The project underwent a major pivot (ADR-035/036) from an *enforced* cage-and-broker access model (`ctx-access`, task lifecycle, `served_nodes`, write-needs-read) to a *lead-by-hooks* model (`ctx-context`, PostToolUse hook injection, content-hash freshness). Retired terms (`ctx-access`, `init-task`, `end-task`, `served_nodes`) are banned outside this ledger and `docs/retired/**`, enforced by `scripts/retired_terms_check.sh` (ADR-051).
- `docs/SPEC.md` itself is retired (ADR-052, moved to `docs/retired/SPEC.md`); its content is redistributed into `.context/intent.md`, `Cargo.toml`/`clippy.toml`, the summarizer prompts (`prompts/summarizer-{leaf,rollup}.md`, which now embed their own line budgets), and this ledger. Don't cite SPEC.md as current.
- The cage (`crates/ctx-cage`) evolved through several ADRs (026→034→040) from Bash+bwrap+broker to a pure-Rust crate to finally a safety-boundary-only sandbox with RW workspace binds, no broker — check the latest ADR (040/046/048/049) before assuming any earlier cage architecture still applies.
- `ctx-verify` (ADR-011/022/047) is the single verification/checkpoint entry point — formats, builds, lints, tests, checks unused deps (`cargo-machete`); explicitly does NOT include `cargo-deny` or module-cycle detection (rejected due to offline/false-positive blockers).
- Several ADRs document validation methodology failures worth reusing as caution: ADR-024 (never conflate infra error with code failure), ADR-027 (a test harness must not mutate what it verifies), ADR-032 (a green result with an absent precondition is a hollow pass — assert preconditions, not just outcomes).
- New ADRs append at the end with the next sequential number; never edit prior entries except to add an explicit "Status/Amended by" note pointing forward.